# üß∞ Windows VM ‚Äì ‚ÄúNo Drives Found‚Äù During Installation in Proxmox

## üß© Problem
While installing **Windows 10/11** or **Windows Server** inside **Proxmox VE**, the Windows Setup screen displayed:

> ‚ÄúNo drives were found. Click Load Driver to provide a mass storage driver for installation.‚Äù

Even though the virtual hard disk was properly configured, Windows could not detect it.

---

## ‚öôÔ∏è Cause
Proxmox uses **VirtIO drivers** to provide optimized, high-performance virtual hardware. However, Windows installation media **does not include** these drivers by default. As a result, the virtualized storage device is invisible to the Windows installer.

---

## ü™Ñ Solution

### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Download and upload VirtIO drivers to Proxmox
From the official Fedora repository:  
üîó [Download virtio-win.iso](https://fedorapeople.org/groups/virt/virtio-win/direct-downloads/latest-virtio/)

Upload this ISO to your Proxmox **ISO Storage** (e.g., `local:iso` or `iso-storage`).

---

### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Attach VirtIO ISO to the VM
In the Proxmox web interface:
1. Select your Windows VM  
2. Go to **Hardware ‚Üí Add ‚Üí CD/DVD Drive**  
3. Choose **Use ISO Image** ‚Üí select `virtio-win.iso`  
4. Set the **Bus/Device** to `IDE` or `SATA` (not VirtIO for the CD drive)

---

### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Restart the VM
Reboot (or stop/start) the VM so the installer can see both ISOs:
- Windows installation ISO  
- VirtIO driver ISO  

---

### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Load the storage driver in Windows setup
When prompted to select a driver:
1. Click **Load Driver ‚Üí Browse**  
2. Navigate to the VirtIO CD (usually `D:` or `E:`)  
3. Open the folder matching your OS version:
   ```
   viostor > w10    # for Windows 10 / 11
   viostor > 2k19   # for Windows Server 2019
   viostor > 2k22   # for Windows Server 2022
   ```
4. Click **OK** ‚Üí select the driver ‚Üí continue installation  
Your virtual disk should now appear.

---

### 5Ô∏è‚É£ Complete setup and install full VirtIO tools
Once Windows is installed:
1. Mount the VirtIO ISO again in Proxmox  
2. Inside Windows, open the CD and run:
   ```
   virtio-win-guest-tools.exe
   ```
This installs all VirtIO components (storage, network, balloon driver, QEMU guest agent, etc.)

---

## üß† Lessons Learned
- Proxmox‚Äôs VirtIO devices offer **enterprise-grade performance**, but require manual drivers for Windows installs.  
- Always keep a copy of the **latest VirtIO ISO** in your Proxmox ISO library.  
- Troubleshooting missing storage drivers simulates **real help desk and IT support scenarios** ‚Äî valuable experience for SOC and IT admin roles.  

---

### ‚úÖ Example VM Hardware Configuration
| Component | Setting |
|------------|----------|
| Disk | `SCSI` using VirtIO SCSI controller |
| Network | `VirtIO (paravirtualized)` |
| CD/DVD 1 | Windows installation ISO |
| CD/DVD 2 | VirtIO drivers ISO |
| BIOS | `OVMF (UEFI)` or `SeaBIOS` |
| Display | `Default` |
| Memory | 4‚Äì8 GB |
| CPU | 2‚Äì4 cores |

---

## üßæ Summary for GitHub
This issue occurred during the setup of a Windows VM within my Proxmox-based homelab. Windows Setup failed to detect the virtual disk because the VirtIO drivers were not preloaded in the installation ISO. After adding the **virtio-win.iso** as a secondary CD/DVD drive and manually loading the correct driver, Windows successfully recognized the disk and installation continued normally.  

This experience reinforced the importance of understanding virtualization hardware layers and driver dependencies ‚Äî both critical skills for IT Help Desk and SOC analyst workflows.  

